hymns.content:
1 To give first thought to them, I worship Surya and Prthivi, and Agni, bright and fair, to hasten their approach.
 Come hither unto us, O Aśvins, with those aids by which in battle you lead the charge and claim the spoil.
 2 Ample, unfailing, they have mounted as it were a chariot, that we may think of you and do your will.
 Come hither unto us, O Aśvins, with those aids by which you help our thoughts to act in holy deeds.
 3 By the might of heavenly nectar you rule supreme, Lord of all these folk; come hither, O Aśvins, with those aids.
 4 By those aids by which the Wanderer through his offspring's might, or the Two-Mothered Son shows swiftest among the swift;
 By those aids by which the wise one acquires his triple lore—come hither, O Aśvins, with those aids.
 5 By those aids by which you freed Rebha and Vandana to behold the light; by those aids by which you saved the barren cow to yield her milk;
 By those aids by which you rescued Antaka from the pit, and Bhujyu with unfailing help.
 And comforted Karkandhu, Vayya, in their woe—come hither, O Aśvins, with those aids.
 6 By those aids by which you gave Śucanti wealth and happy home, and made the fiery pit friendly for Atri’s sake;
 By those aids by which you guarded Purukutsa, Pṛśnigu—come hither, O Aśvins, with those aids.
 7 By those aids by which you made Parāvṛj see and walk, and freed the swallowed quail;
 By those aids by which you quickened the most sweet exhaustless flood, and comforted Vasiṣṭha, who never decays;
 And to Śrutarya, Kutsa, Narya gave your help—come hither, O Aśvins, with those aids.
 8 By those aids by which you gave power to Parāvṛj to see and walk, and freed the blind and lame;
 By those aids by which you set at liberty the swallowed quail—come hither, O Aśvins, with those aids.
 9 By those aids by which you brought sweet rain for Dīrgh

1. WITH wisdom I offer these vibrant hymns to Bhāvya, the dweller by the Sindhu river;
 For he, unvanquished King, seeking glory, has provided me with a thousand sacrifices.

2. The King gave me a hundred necklaces, and a hundred gift-horses, I received them both at once;
 From his cows, a thousand, I Kakṣīvān. His immortal glory spreads to the heavens.

3. Dusky-hoofed horses stood beside me, ten chariots, Svanaya’s gift, with mares to pull them;
 Sixty thousand cows followed behind. Kakṣīvān gained them as the day was closing.

4. Before a thousand, forty bay horses of the ten carriages’ master lead the long procession;
 Joyfully Kakṣīvān’s sons and Pajra’s have grounded the decorated horses with pearl-trimmed harnesses.

5. Earlier, I accepted an earlier gift for you, eight good milkers and three harnessed horses,
 Pajras, with your wagons and your great kin, like a troop of subjects, eager for glory.

6. [He speaks]. Close, close approach; gently touch me. Do not think my few hairs: I am entirely covered with wool, like a Kashmir goat.

7. [He speaks]. Near, near come; touch me gently. Do not think my few hairs: I am entirely covered with wool, like a Kashmir goat.

1. Wondrous let your arrival be, wondrous with help, you Bountiful Ones,
Maruts, who shine like snakes do.
2. Far be from us, O Maruts, you generous ones, your swift arrows;
Far from us be the rock you throw.
3. O Bountiful Givers, do not touch, O Maruts, the folk of Tṛṇskanda;
Raise us up so we may live.
